379	
380	After Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime} the cohomology-of-an-open carriers $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,X$ are well-defined and carry the canonical $\Module k$-structure inherited from \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.instModule} through the \lstinline{noncomputable abbrev} reducibility. The natural follow-on companion, mirroring iter-010's $H^0$ bridge for the parallel $\HModule$ (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_zero_linearEquiv}), is the identification of the degree-zero piece $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,0\,X$ with a Hom group: this is the algebraic prerequisite that downstream Stein-factorization-derived $H^0(C, \struct C) \simeq k$ arguments on a connected proper $k$-curve will eventually consume.
381	
382	The Lean implementation reuses Mathlib's \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀} (file \lstinline{Mathlib/Algebra/Homology/DerivedCategory/Ext/Linear.lean}), specialised to the $\Linear k$-enriched abelian category $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$ (the $\Linear k$ enrichment is auto-inferable from \lstinline{HasSheafify} via \lstinline{Sheaf.linear}).
383	
384	\begin{definition}[$H^0$ as a $k$-linear Hom group, $\HModulePrime$ flavor]
385	  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_zero_linearEquiv}
386	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_zero_linearEquiv}
387	  \leanok
388	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime, thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK, thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}
389	  Let $k$ be a field, $(C, J)$ a Grothendieck site with $\HasWeakSheafify\,J\,(\mathrm{Type}\,u)$, $\HasSheafify\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$, and $\HasExt(\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k))$, $X : C$, and $F : \Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$. Then there is a canonical $k$-linear equivalence
390	  \[
391	    \mathtt{HModulePrime\_zero\_linearEquiv}_X \,:\, \HModulePrime\,k\,F\,0\,X \;\simeq_k\; \bigl((\mathtt{presheafToSheaf}\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)).\mathrm{obj}\,((\yoneda \circ \free_k).\mathrm{obj}\,X) \,\to\, F\bigr)
392	  \]
393	  given by \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀}.
394	\end{definition}
395	
396	\begin{proof}
397	  \leanok
398	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime}
399	  Direct from \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀} applied to the abelian category $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$, which is $\Linear k$-enriched (auto-inferable from the prerequisites of Section~\ref{sec:moduleK_prereqs}) and has $\HasExt$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}). The $\noncomputable$ \lstinline{abbrev} reducibility of $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,0\,X$ (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime}) lets instance synthesis unfold the wrapper to the underlying $\Ext^0$ group, and \lstinline{linearEquiv₀} returns the $\Module k$-linear bijection between that $\Ext^0$ group and the corresponding Hom group in the sheaf category. The closure body is therefore a one-liner \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀}; iter-015 plan-agent \lstinline{lean_run_code} probe confirms the closure compiles end-to-end against current Mathlib + project state, kernel-only axioms.
400	\end{proof}
401	
402	\begin{remark}[Choice of \texttt{def} over \texttt{abbrev}]
403	  Unlike $\HModulePrime$ itself (which uses \lstinline{noncomputable abbrev} to keep the wrapper reducible for instance synthesis on the underlying $\Ext$ group), the $H^0$-bridge auxiliary uses \lstinline{noncomputable def}. Reason: the result is a $\simeq_k$ between two known types whose $\Module\,k$ and $\AddCommGroup$ instances are already inferable through the iter-014 \lstinline{HModule'} reducibility; a \lstinline{def} form is fine, and \lstinline{abbrev} would over-expose the body without additional benefit. This mirrors iter-010's choice for the parallel $\HModule\_zero\_linearEquiv$ (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_zero_linearEquiv}).
404	\end{remark}
